 Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Paulett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Leicestershire):","nickname from Middle English <i>pail(l)et</i> ‘bed or mattress of straw, pallet’, sometimes for someone who made or sold pallets.","variant of   Pollitt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pollitt","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from the personal name <i>Hippolytus</i>, Greek <i>Hippolytos</i>, comprising elements meaning ‘horse’ + ‘to release’ (see   Hyppolite  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Paulett was born in 1210, in Pawlett, Somerset, England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir. William Paulet. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs William de PAULET. He died in 1281, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1210–1281":"1210–1281","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1235–1314":"1235–1314","1237–Male":"1237–Surnud","1245–1281":"1245–1281","1271–1325":"1271–1325","1185–1209":"1185–1209","About 1245":"umbes 1245","1185":"1185","1271":"1271